'''Billie Eilish Pirate Baird O'Connell''' ({{IPAc-en|'|aI|l|I|S}} {{Respell|EYE|lish}};<ref name="BBCPirate">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-40580489|title=Billie Eilish: Is she pop's best new hope?|last=Savage|first=Mark|work=[[BBC News]]|date=July 15, 2017|quote="...It's eye-''lish'', like eyelash with a lish."|access-date=July 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721111611/http://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-40580489|archive-date=July 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> born December 18, 2001) is an American singer and songwriter. She first gained public attention in 2015 with her debut single "[[Ocean Eyes (song)|Ocean Eyes]]", written and produced by her brother [[Finneas O'Connell]], with whom she collaborates on music and live shows. In 2017, she released her debut [[extended play]] (EP), ''[[Don't Smile at Me]]''. Commercially successful, it reached the top 15 of record charts in numerous countries, including the US, UK, Canada, and Australia.

Eilish's first studio album, ''[[When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?]]'' (2019), debuted atop the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and [[UK Albums Chart]]. It was one of the year's best-selling albums, buoyed by the success of its fifth single, "[[Bad Guy (Billie Eilish song)|Bad Guy]]", Eilish's first number-one on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. This made her the first artist born in the 21st century to release a chart-topping single. The next year, Eilish performed the theme song "[[No Time to Die (song)|No Time to Die]]" for the [[James Bond]] film [[No Time to Die|of the same name]], which topped the [[UK Singles Chart]] and won the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] in 2022. Her subsequent singles "[[Everything I Wanted]]", "[[My Future]]", "[[Therefore I Am (song)|Therefore I Am]]", and "[[Your Power]]" peaked in the top 10 in the US and UK. Her second studio album, ''[[Happier Than Ever]]'' (2021), topped the charts in 25 countries. She wrote and performed "[[What Was I Made For?]]" for the fantasy film ''[[Barbie (film)|Barbie]]'' (2023), which became her second number-one single in the UK and earned her a second Academy Award. In 2024, she released her third album, ''[[Hit Me Hard and Soft]]'', to critical acclaim.

Eilish has received [[List of awards and nominations received by Billie Eilish|multiple accolades]], including nine [[Grammy Award]]s, two [[American Music Awards]], two [[Guinness World Records]], three [[MTV Video Music Award]]s, three [[Brit Awards]], two [[Golden Globe Awards]], and two [[Academy Awards]]. She is the second artist in Grammy history to win [[Big Four (Grammy Awards)|all four general field categories]]—[[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]],  [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]], as well as [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]]—in the same year. Eilish is also the first person born in the 21st century to win an Academy Award and the youngest ever two-time winner.<ref name="Oscar">{{cite web|date=March 27, 2022|title=Billie Eilish Becomes First Oscar Winner Born in 21st Century With 'No Time to Die'|url=https://www.thewrap.com/billie-eilish-oscar-win-record-second-youngest-songwriter/|last=Knolle|first=Sharon|access-date=June 28, 2023|website=[[TheWrap]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230311075555/https://www.thewrap.com/billie-eilish-oscar-win-record-second-youngest-songwriter/|archive-date=March 11, 2023|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=MSN |url=https://www.msn.com/ |access-date=2024-03-11 |website=www.msn.com |archive-date=October 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029064023/https://www.msn.com/ |url-status=live }}</ref> She was featured on ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's inaugural [[Time 100 Next|''Time'' 100 Next list]] in 2019 and the [[Time 100|''Time'' 100]] in 2021.<ref>{{cite web|first=Madison|last=Bloom|date=September 15, 2021|title=Billie Eilish, Lil Nas X, Bad Bunny Make 2021 Time 100 List|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/billie-eilish-lil-nas-x-bad-bunny-make-2021-time-100-list/|access-date=September 16, 2021 |website=Pitchfork|archive-date=September 16, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210916045910/https://pitchfork.com/news/billie-eilish-lil-nas-x-bad-bunny-make-2021-time-100-list/|url-status=live}}</ref> According to the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) and ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', Eilish is the 26th-highest-certified digital singles artist<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=top_tallies&ttt=TAS|title=Recording Industry Association of America Gold & Platinum|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|access-date=June 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126081620/http://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=top_tallies&ttt=TAS|archive-date=January 26, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and one of the most successful artists of the [[2010s in music|2010s]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Billboard's Top Artists of the 2010s|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/decade-end/top-artists|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210511033038/https://www.billboard.com/charts/decade-end/top-artists|archive-date=May 11, 2021|access-date=May 11, 2021|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=October 31, 2019}}</ref> She was honored as one of the [[100 Women (BBC)|BBC 100 Women]] in December 2022.<ref>{{Cite news |title=BBC 100 Women 2022: Who is on the list this year? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/resources/idt-75af095e-21f7-41b0-9c5f-a96a5e0615c1 |access-date=December 10, 2022 |agency=BBC News |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230413193225/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/resources/idt-75af095e-21f7-41b0-9c5f-a96a5e0615c1 |archive-date=April 13, 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref>

Eilish has a history of political activism, focusing on [[Climate movement|climate change awareness]], [[Reproductive rights|women's reproductive rights]], [[gender equality]], and [[animal rights]].

== Early life ==
[[File:Billie Eilish and Maggie Baird Nov 2018.png|thumb|upright=0.95|Eilish with her mother, [[Maggie Baird]], in November 2018]]
Billie Eilish Pirate Baird O'Connell was born in Los Angeles, California, on December 18, 2001.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8545478/billie-eilish-when-we-all-fall-asleep-biggest-album-2019| title= The Year in Charts 2019: Billie Eilish's 'When We All Fall Asleep...' Is Biggest Album of the Year| magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date= December 5, 2019|access-date= December 31, 2019|url-access= subscription| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191226080532/https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8545478/billie-eilish-when-we-all-fall-asleep-biggest-album-2019|archive-date= December 26, 2019|url-status= live}}</ref> She is the daughter of actress and teacher [[Maggie Baird]]<ref>{{cite web| title= Maggie Baird |url= https://www.groundlings.com/people/maggie-baird |website=The Groundlings Theatre & School|access-date= November 17, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191116235106/https://www.groundlings.com/people/maggie-baird|archive-date= November 16, 2019|url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/billie-eilish-fun-facts-no-soda-list|title=Billie Eilish Isn't Allowed to Drink Soda|work=[[W (magazine)|W]] |date=July 31, 2019|accessdate=June 28, 2021|archive-date=June 28, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210628185517/https://www.wmagazine.com/story/billie-eilish-fun-facts-no-soda-list|url-status=live}}</ref> and actor Patrick O'Connell,<!--THIS ARTICLE IS NOT ON THE PARENTS. Keep succinct; do not add a list of film/tv credits, or sides jobs like construction; as per NYT and other sources, the arts was their primary profession, and their side jobs are not notable content here [[WP:ONUS]].--><ref name="Gomez">{{cite web |last1=Gomez |first1=Jasmine |title=Here's Everything You Need to Know About Billie Eilish's Parents and Brother, Finneas |url=https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/music/a29073914/billie-eilish-parents-family-siblings/ |website=[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines]]|location=New York City|date=September 16, 2019|access-date=December 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107182656/https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/music/a29073914/billie-eilish-parents-family-siblings/|archive-date=January 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> both of whom are also musicians and work on Eilish's tours.<ref name="Buzz">{{cite web|first=Alessa|last=Dominguez|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/pdominguez/is-billie-eilish-really-that-weird|title=Is Billie Eilish Really That "Weird"?|work=[[BuzzFeed News]]|date=August 17, 2019|access-date=December 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902185411/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/pdominguez/is-billie-eilish-really-that-weird|archive-date=September 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Tatiana">{{cite magazine|first=Tatiana|last=Cirisano|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8504254/finneas-oconnell-interview-billie-eilish-brother-co-writer|title=Sibling Revelry: Finneas, Billie Eilish's Brother & Co-Writer, Steps Out|magazine=Billboard|date=March 27, 2019|access-date=December 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401144913/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8504254/finneas-oconnell-interview-billie-eilish-brother-co-writer|archive-date=April 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Haskell"/> Eilish is of Irish and Scottish descent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/an-interview-with-billie-eilish-pops-ferocious-new-enigma-21675864|title=An Interview with Billie Eilish: Pop's Ferocious New Enigma|last=Power|first=Ed|work=Hotpress|date=February 1, 2018|access-date=November 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108070507/https://www.hotpress.com/music/an-interview-with-billie-eilish-pops-ferocious-new-enigma-21675864|archive-date=November 8, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She was conceived via [[in vitro fertilization]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aol.com/article/entertainment/2019/10/02/billie-eilish-howard-stern-interview-ivf-parents-brother/23825483/|title=Billie Eilish finds out she was conceived via IVF during Howard Stern interview|publisher=[[AOL]]|date=October 2, 2019|access-date=February 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200614221836/https://www.aol.com/article/entertainment/2019/10/02/billie-eilish-howard-stern-interview-ivf-parents-brother/23825483/|archive-date=June 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Her middle name, Eilish, was originally meant to be her first name, while Pirate was to be her middle name.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insider.com/who-is-billie-eilish-cool-facts-2020-2|title=From her real name to her natural hair color, here are answers to 13 questions you have about Billie Eilish|last=Vanderberg|first=Madison|date=February 26, 2020|website=[[Insider Inc.|Insider]]|access-date=March 9, 2020|archive-date=February 23, 2021|archive-url=https://archive.today/20210223045927/https://www.insider.com/who-is-billie-eilish-cool-facts-2020-2|url-status=live}}</ref> She was raised in the [[Highland Park, Los Angeles|Highland Park]] neighborhood of Los Angeles.<ref name="MTVUK">{{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/billie-eilish/news/get-to-know-billie-eilish|title=Get to Know: Billie Eilish|website=[[MTV UK]]|access-date=December 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516015713/http://www.mtv.co.uk/billie-eilish/news/get-to-know-billie-eilish|archive-date=May 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Trammell">{{cite news|first=Kendell|last=Trammell|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/09/entertainment/billie-eilish-no-1-album/index.html|title=This 17-year-old is the first artist born in the 2000s to have a No. 1 album|work=[[CNN]]|date=April 10, 2019|access-date=December 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126181433/https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/09/entertainment/billie-eilish-no-1-album/index.html|archive-date=January 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>

Eilish and her brother Finneas were [[Homeschooling|homeschooled]] by Baird, a decision their parents made to spend time with them and give them the freedom to pursue their interests.<ref name="Gomez"/><ref name="Haskell">{{cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/billie-eilish-cover-march-2020|title=How Billie Eilish Is Reinventing Pop Stardom|date=February 3, 2020|last=Haskell|first=Rob|work=Vogue|publisher=Condé Nast|access-date=May 2, 2020|archive-date=May 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200506134758/https://www.vogue.com/article/billie-eilish-cover-march-2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Baird taught Eilish and Finneas the basics of songwriting.<ref name="Josh"/> Eilish said her brother and mother inspired her to get into music.<ref name="Gonzalez"/> Their parents encouraged the siblings to express themselves and explore whatever they wanted, including art, dancing, and acting.<ref name="Buzz"/><ref name="Josh">{{cite magazine|first=Petra|last=Collins|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/billie-eilish-cover-story-triumph-weird-863603/|title=Billie Eilish And the Triumph of the Weird|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=July 31, 2019|access-date=January 26, 2020|url-access=limited|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126113251/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/billie-eilish-cover-story-triumph-weird-863603/|archive-date=January 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Eilish performed at talent shows and joined the [[Los Angeles Children's Chorus]] at age eight.<ref name="MathiasV"/><ref name="Josh"/> At age six, she started playing the ukulele.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/billie-eilish-beatles-carpool-karaoke-james-corden-1203449834/|title=Billie Eilish Plays the Beatles and the First Song She Ever Wrote on 'Carpool Karaoke'|work=Variety|date=December 20, 2019|last=Aswad|first=Jem|access-date=October 16, 2021|archive-date=October 16, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211016202141/https://variety.com/2019/music/news/billie-eilish-beatles-carpool-karaoke-james-corden-1203449834/|url-status=live}}</ref> She wrote her first "real" song at age 11 for her mother's songwriting class. The song is about the zombie apocalypse, inspired by the television series ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]'', from which she took script lines and episode titles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://junkee.com/billie-eilish-interview-2017/123864|title=Meet The 15-Year-Old Everyone Says Is Pop's Next Big Thing|work=[[Junkee]]|first=Jules|last=Lefevre|date=September 19, 2017|access-date=February 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205164813/https://junkee.com/billie-eilish-interview-2017/123864|archive-date=February 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Gonzalez">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/art-books-music/a13040159/billie-eilish-interview/|title=Billie Eilish Is a 15-Year-Old Pop Prodigy—And She's Intimidating as Hell|magazine=[[Harper's Bazaar]]|first=Erics|last=Gonzales|date=October 19, 2017|access-date=February 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305091727/https://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/art-books-music/a13040159/billie-eilish-interview/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Eilish took some acting auditions, which she disliked, but she enjoyed recording background dialogue for crowd scenes and worked on the films ''[[Diary of a Wimpy Kid (2010 film)|Diary of a Wimpy Kid]]'', ''[[Ramona and Beezus]]'', and the [[X-Men (film series)|''X-Men'' series]].<ref name="Josh"/> Eilish also took dance classes until 2016, when a growth plate injury ended her dance career and she focused on recording music.<ref name="bill3" /><ref name="Marsh" /><ref name="MathiasV" />

== Career ==
=== 2015–2017: ''Don't Smile at Me'' ===
{{Main|Don't Smile at Me}}
In 2015, 13-year-old Eilish began working on songs with her brother Finneas, who had been writing and producing for several years and had his own band.<ref name="Marsh"/><ref name="MathiasV"/><ref name="Tatiana"/> The first songs they recorded together were called "She's Broken" and "Fingers Crossed", the former written by Finneas and the latter by Eilish. "We recorded them and put them out on [[SoundCloud]], just for fun," she recalled.<ref>{{cite web|last=Aswad|first=Jem|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/billie-eilish-finneas-oconnell-songwriting-1203421768/|title=Billie Eilish and Brother/Co-Writer Finneas Get Deep About Songwriting|work=Variety|date=December 4, 2019|access-date=December 16, 2020|archive-date=June 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200608003654/https://variety.com/2019/music/news/billie-eilish-finneas-oconnell-songwriting-1203421768/|url-status=live}}<br />{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/jellyjrnl/who-is-billie-eilish-15683d980a58|title=WHO IS: Billie Eilish. Meet the 16 year old american future...|first=Laura|last=Coelho de Almeida|work=Jellyjrn|date=November 22, 2018|access-date=December 17, 2020}}<!--<br />{{cite web|url=https://www.thelamron.com/posts/2017/9/14/young-artist-challenges-expectations-of-mainstream-indie-genre|title=Young artist challenges expectations of mainstream indie genre|website=The Lamron|date=September 14, 2017|access-date=December 17, 2020}}--></ref>

On November 18, 2015, Eilish released the song "[[Ocean Eyes (song)|Ocean Eyes]]". The track was written, mixed, and produced by Finneas, who had originally created it for his band the Slightlys before deciding it would be a better fit for Eilish's vocals.<ref name="Tatiana"/><ref name="Insider">{{cite web|url=https://www.insider.com/billie-eilish-songs-ranked-best-worst|title=Every Billie Eilish song, ranked|first1=Callie|last1=Ahlgrim|first2=Libby|last2=Torres|first3=Claudia|last3=Willen|access-date=April 5, 2020|date=March 18, 2020|website=[[Insider Inc.|Insider]]|archive-date=September 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200916030546/https://www.insider.com/billie-eilish-songs-ranked-best-worst|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="MathiasV">{{cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/billie-eilish-pops-next-it-girl|title=Meet Billie Eilish, Pop's Next It Girl|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|first=Mathias|last=Rosenzweig|date=August 9, 2016|access-date=February 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529135313/https://www.vogue.com/article/billie-eilish-pops-next-it-girl|archive-date=May 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Marsh">{{cite web|first=Ariana|last=Marsh|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/how-billie-eilishs-ocean-eyes-turned-her-into-an-overnight-sensation|title=How Billie Eilish's "Ocean Eyes" Turned Her Into an Overnight Sensation|work=[[Teen Vogue]]|date=February 24, 2017|access-date=December 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225112916/https://www.teenvogue.com/story/how-billie-eilishs-ocean-eyes-turned-her-into-an-overnight-sensation|archive-date=December 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He gave it to Eilish when Fred Diaz, her dance teacher at the Revolution Dance Center, asked them to write a song for choreography. The siblings uploaded the song to [[SoundCloud]], where Diaz could access and download it.<ref name="Marsh" /><ref name="MathiasV" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/discovery-billie-eilish|title=Discovery: Billie Eilish|last=Weiss|first=Haley|website=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|date=February 27, 2017|access-date=July 31, 2020|archive-date=July 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711202626/https://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/discovery-billie-eilish|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/story/2020-01-24/billie-eilish-finneas-julia-butters-revolution-dance-montrose|title=What do Billie Eilish and 'Once Upon a Time ... in Hollywood' have in common? A Montrose dance studio|last=McNamara|first=Mary|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 24, 2020|access-date=July 31, 2020|archive-date=October 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201001063157/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/story/2020-01-24/billie-eilish-finneas-julia-butters-revolution-dance-montrose|url-status=live|url-access=limited}}</ref> The song received several hundred thousand listens in two weeks, and Finneas's manager, Danny Rukasin, reached out to him to discuss Eilish's potential. Rukasin felt she could achieve significant success with Finneas's help.{{refn|<ref name="bill" /><ref name="Buzz"/><ref name="i-m-i.ru 08.03.2020">{{cite web|url=https://i-m-i.ru/post/billie-eilish-debut|title=Не просто альбом, сделанный в спальне. Сколько стоила запись пластинки Билли Айлиш|trans-title=Not simply a record made in her bedroom. How much did Billie Eilish's album cost to make?|publisher=Institute for Musical Initiatives (magazine)|date=March 8, 2020|access-date=December 16, 2020|language=Russian|archive-date=January 20, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210120001358/https://i-m-i.ru/post/billie-eilish-debut|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="mn"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Stassen|first=Murray|url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/behind-billie-eilish-meet-the-managers-guiding-the-artists-global-success/|title=Behind Billie Eilish: Meet The Managers Guiding The Artist's Global Success|publisher=Music Business Worldwide|date=May 2, 2019|access-date=January 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191208054359/https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/behind-billie-eilish-meet-the-managers-guiding-the-artists-global-success/|archive-date=December 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>}}

In January 2016, Finneas and his manager arranged a deal in which [[Apple Music]] signed Eilish to [[A&R]] company Platoon, specializing in packaging emerging artists before they get a major-label contract.<ref name="mn"/><ref name="Buzz"/><ref name="i-m-i.ru 08.03.2020" /> Eilish then got a publicist, who connected her to the luxury fashion brand [[Chanel]], and a stylist, both of whom helped shape her image.<ref name="Buzz"/> On March 24, 2016, a music video for "Ocean Eyes" directed by Megan Thompson premiered on Eilish's official YouTube channel.<ref name="stereo">{{cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/1867003/billie-eilish-ocean-eyes-video-stereogum-premiere/mp3s/|title=Billie Eilish – 'Ocean Eyes' Video (Stereogum Premiere)|last=DeVille|first=Chris|website=[[Stereogum]]|date=March 23, 2016|access-date=July 31, 2020|archive-date=April 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401152012/https://www.stereogum.com/1867003/billie-eilish-ocean-eyes-video-stereogum-premiere/mp3s/|url-status=live}}</ref> "Ocean Eyes" and Eilish received praise and promotion from various media outlets and marketers, including radio stations and music supervisors such as [[Beats 1]], [[KCRW]], [[BBC Radio 1]], [[Zane Lowe]], [[Jason Kramer]], [[Annie Mac]], and [[Chris Douridas]].{{refn|<ref name="Tatiana"/><ref name="SXSW"/><ref name="Spencer">{{cite web|last=Kornhaber|first=Spencer|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/01/why-billie-eilish-swept-grammys/605587/|title=How Pop's Biggest Weirdo Swept the Grammys|work=[[The Atlantic]]|date=January 27, 2020|access-date=January 28, 2020|url-access=limited|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127233908/https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/01/why-billie-eilish-swept-grammys/605587/|archive-date=January 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="MathiasID">{{cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_us/article/xwdqn3/exclusive-14-year-old-singer-billie-eilish-returns-with-a-new-dance-video|title=Exclusive: 14-Year-Old Singer Billie Eilish Returns With A New Dance Video|work=[[i-D]]|first=Mathias|last=Rosenzweig|date=November 22, 2016|access-date=January 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113171637/https://i-d.vice.com/en_us/article/xwdqn3/exclusive-14-year-old-singer-billie-eilish-returns-with-a-new-dance-video|archive-date=November 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>}}

On June 23, 2016, Eilish and Finneas released "[[Six Feet Under (Billie Eilish song)|Six Feet Under]]" on SoundCloud as her second single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/billieeilish/six-feet-under|title=six feet under by Billie Eilish|publisher=[[SoundCloud]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812131942/https://soundcloud.com/billieeilish/six-feet-under|archive-date=August 12, 2016|access-date=December 16, 2020}}<br />{{cite web|last=O'Connor Marotta|first=Michael|url=https://vanyaland.com/2016/06/23/vmusic-first-listen-billie-eilish-six-feet/|title=V:Music First Listen: Billie Eilish, 'Six Feet Under'|website=Vanyaland|date=June 23, 2020|access-date=December 16, 2020|archive-date=January 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129042808/https://vanyaland.com/2016/06/23/vmusic-first-listen-billie-eilish-six-feet/|url-status=live}}</ref> A homemade music video for the song was released on June 30, 2016.<ref name="Billboard">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8546086/billie-eilish-songs-every-superfan-should-know|title=10 Billie Eilish Songs Every Superfan Should Know|last=Spruch|first=Kristen|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=December 12, 2019|access-date=May 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200626230142/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8546086/billie-eilish-songs-every-superfan-should-know|archive-date=June 26, 2020|url-status=live}}<br />{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FQ0iq10ULNA|title=Billie Eilish – Six Feet Under |via=YouTube|date=June 30, 2020|access-date=December 16, 2020|archive-date=January 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105212508/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FQ0iq10ULNA|url-status=live}}</ref> It was directed by Eilish and edited by her mother, Maggie Baird.<ref name="Billboard"/>

In August 2016, Justin Lubliner, who had noticed Eilish's talent in 2015 when he first heard "Ocean Eyes", signed her to Darkroom and [[Interscope Records]].<ref name="bill">{{cite magazine|last=Havens|first=Lyndsey|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8510552/billie-eilish-billboard-cover-story-2019|title=Why All Eyes Are on Billie Eilish, the New Model for Streaming Era Success|magazine=Billboard|date=May 9, 2019|access-date=January 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127000454/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8510552/billie-eilish-billboard-cover-story-2019|archive-date=January 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hissong|first=Samantha|url=https://hitsdailydouble.com/news&id=315869&title+INTRODUCING-JUSTIN-LUBLINER|title=Rumor Mill – Introducing Justin Lubliner|work=Hits Daily Double|date=April 2, 2019|access-date=December 16, 2020|archive-date=October 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201031171521/https://hitsdailydouble.com/news%26id%3D315869%26title+INTRODUCING-JUSTIN-LUBLINER|url-status=live}}</ref> He developed her rollout as an artist, taking inspiration from the model of hip hop artists such as [[Travis Scott]] and [[Chance the Rapper]], not relying on one big single and focusing on creating a "persona and distinct aesthetic".<ref name="bill3">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7736384/billie-eilish-interview-bellyache-debut-album|title=Billie Eilish Is Pop's Most Impressive 15-Year-Old|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=March 23, 2017|access-date=July 31, 2020|archive-date=August 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200819171509/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7736384/billie-eilish-interview-bellyache-debut-album|url-status=live}}</ref> Darkroom and Interscope Records re-released "Six Feet Under" and "Ocean Eyes" as singles for digital download and [[Streaming media|streaming]] on November 17 and 18, 2016, respectively.<ref name="Tidal - Six Feet Under">{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/66991655|title=Six Feet Under / Billie Eilish|publisher=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|date=November 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201216164534/https://listen.tidal.com/album/66991655|archive-date=December 16, 2020|access-date=December 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name="Tidal - Ocean Eyes">{{cite news|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/67043776 |title=Ocean Eyes / Billie Eilish|publisher=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|date=November 18, 2016 |access-date=December 16, 2020 |archive-date=December 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201216020640/https://listen.tidal.com/album/67043776 |url-status=live}}<br />{{cite web |url=https://www.ultratop.be/fr/song/1753ab/Billie-Eilish-Ocean-Eyes|title=ultratop.be – Billie Eilish – Ocean Eyes |website=[[Ultratop]] |access-date=January 30, 2020 |archive-date=May 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200526120455/https://www.ultratop.be/fr/song/1753ab/Billie-Eilish-Ocean-Eyes |url-status=live}}</ref> On November 22, 2016, a dance performance music video for "Ocean Eyes" was uploaded to Eilish's YouTube channel.<ref>{{cite AV media|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hG4lT4fxj8M |title=Billie Eilish – Ocean Eyes (Dance Performance Video) |access-date=April 14, 2017 |date=November 22, 2016 |via=YouTube |archive-date=April 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401104625/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hG4lT4fxj8M |url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:The Hi Hat - Billie Eilish 08 10 2017 -3 (36529010754).jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|left|Eilish performing in August 2017]]
On January 14, 2017, Eilish released an [[Extended play|EP]] with four remixes by Astronomyy, [[Blackbear (musician)|Blackbear]], [[Goldhouse]], and [[Cautious Clay]] for "Ocean Eyes",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/ocean-eyes-the-remixes-ep/id1195571727 |title=Ocean Eyes (The Remixes) – EP by Billie Eilish on Apple Music |date=January 13, 2017 |access-date=April 14, 2017 |publisher=iTunes Store (UK) |archive-date=April 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401155123/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/ocean-eyes-the-remixes-ep/id1195571727 |url-status=live}}</ref> and another EP for "Six Feet Under" featuring remixes by Blu J, [[Gazzo (producer)|Gazzo]], Jerry Folk, and Aire Atlantica.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/six-feet-under-the-remixes-ep/1445297971 |title=Six Feet Under (The Remixes) – EP by Billie Eilish|publisher=iTunes |access-date=May 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217021817/https://music.apple.com/us/album/six-feet-under-the-remixes-ep/1445297971 |archive-date=December 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> After the success of the "Ocean Eyes" remixes, Eilish released "[[Bellyache (Billie Eilish song)|Bellyache]]" on February 24, 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://tidal.com/browse/album/70539823 |title=Bellyache – Single by Billie Eilish |publisher=Tidal |access-date=September 12, 2020 |archive-date=November 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116125916/https://tidal.com/browse/album/70539823|url-status=live}}</ref> A video for the song was released on March 22, 2017, directed by Miles and AJ.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://vmagazine.com/article/billie-eilish-losing-mind-new-music-video-bellyache/ |title=Watch Billie Eilish Lose Her Mind in New Video for 'Bellyache' |last=Monroe |first=Ian David |website=[[V (American magazine)|V]] |date=March 22, 2017|access-date=September 9, 2020 |archive-date=June 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602171555/http://vmagazine.com/article/billie-eilish-losing-mind-new-music-video-bellyache/|url-status=live}}</ref> Eilish released "[[Bored (song)|Bored]]" on March 30, 2017, as part of the soundtrack to the [[Netflix]] series ''[[13 Reasons Why]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/72500447|title=Bored by Billie Eilish|publisher=Tidal|access-date=June 19, 2020|archive-date=November 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201124232328/https://listen.tidal.com/album/72500447|url-status=live}}</ref> A video for "Bored" was released on June 26, 2017.<ref name="ny">{{cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/music/news/a46236/watch-billie-eilish-bored-video-now/|title=Watch Billie Eilish's 'Bored' Video Now|last=Tang|first=Estelle|website=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]|date=June 26, 2017|access-date=November 12, 2020|archive-date=November 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116011016/https://www.elle.com/culture/music/news/a46236/watch-billie-eilish-bored-video-now/|url-status=live}}</ref> In March of the same year, Apple Music showcased Eilish at the [[South by Southwest]] music festival.<ref name="mn" /><ref name="SXSW">{{cite web|url=https://schedule.sxsw.com/2017/events/MS37872|title=SXSW 2017 Schedule|publisher=[[South by Southwest]]|access-date=January 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129042804/https://schedule.sxsw.com/2017/events/MS37872|archive-date=January 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On June 30, 2017, Eilish released "[[Watch (Billie Eilish song)|Watch]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/0gHg1JLD8DoDgkfz7V2Ygz?nd=1|title=watch by Billie Eilish on Spotify|date=June 30, 2017|publisher=[[Spotify]]|access-date=January 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131040553/https://open.spotify.com/album/0gHg1JLD8DoDgkfz7V2Ygz?nd=1|archive-date=January 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Eilish released another single, "[[Copycat (Billie Eilish song)|Copycat]]", on July 14, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umusic.ca/press-releases/billie-eilish-releases-new-single-copycat/|title=Billie Eilish Releases New Single 'Copycat'|publisher=[[Universal Music Group]]|access-date=May 25, 2020|archive-date=May 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200524061037/http://www.umusic.ca/press-releases/billie-eilish-releases-new-single-copycat/|url-status=live}}</ref> and announced the release of her debut EP, ''[[Don't Smile at Me]]''.<ref name="bill18">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7865245/billie-eilish-debut-ep-dont-smile-at-me-tour|title=15-Year-Old Pop Prodigy Billie Eilish Announces Debut EP & First-Ever Tour|last=Crisano|first=Tatiana|magazine=Billboard|date=July 14, 2017|access-date=May 31, 2020|archive-date=June 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626180801/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7865245/billie-eilish-debut-ep-dont-smile-at-me-tour|url-status=live}}</ref> Eilish later released "[[Idontwannabeyouanymore]]" and "[[My Boy (Billie Eilish song)|My Boy]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://earmilk.com/2017/07/21/billie-eilish-continues-to-flourish-as-a-bladesmith-with-new-track-idontwannabeyouanymore/|title=Billie Eilish continues to flourish with new track 'idontwannabeyouanymore'|website=[[Earmilk]]|last=Bartlet|first=Jess|date=July 27, 2017|access-date=August 24, 2020|archive-date=April 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421104031/https://earmilk.com/2017/07/21/billie-eilish-continues-to-flourish-as-a-bladesmith-with-new-track-idontwannabeyouanymore/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="baeble">{{cite web|url=https://www.baeblemusic.com/musicblog/7-31-2017/billie-eilish-continues-to-impress-with-new-track-my-boy.html|title=Billie Eilish Continues to Impress with New Track 'my boy'|website=Baeble Music|first=Olivia|last=Lewis|date=July 31, 2017|access-date=October 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014143009/https://www.baeblemusic.com/musicblog/7-31-2017/billie-eilish-continues-to-impress-with-new-track-my-boy.html|archive-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref> On August 11, 2017, Eilish released ''Don't Smile at Me''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://earmilk.com/2017/08/11/billie-eilish-releases-lush-debut-ep-dont-smile-at-me/|title=Billie Eilish releases lush debut EP 'dont smile at me'|first=Smither|last=Tanis|website=Earmilk|date=August 11, 2017|access-date=March 31, 2020|archive-date=July 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702232205/https://earmilk.com/2017/08/11/billie-eilish-releases-lush-debut-ep-dont-smile-at-me/|url-status=live}}</ref> The EP was a sleeper hit, reaching number 14 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/billie-eilish/chart-history/tlp/|title=Billie Eilish Chart History (Billboard 200)|magazine=Billboard|access-date=September 16, 2020|archive-date=September 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200930063231/https://www.billboard.com/music/billie-eilish/chart-history/TLP|url-status=live}}</ref> Eilish embarked on the Don't Smile at Me Tour throughout October 2017 in support of her EP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://atwoodmagazine.com/live-billie-eilish-philadelphia-2017/|title=Live: Billie Eilish Is A Stunning Force At Philadelphia's World Cafe Live|last=Almeida|first=Nicole|website=Atwood Magazine|date=October 25, 2017|access-date=September 16, 2020|archive-date=October 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201023032434/https://atwoodmagazine.com/live-billie-eilish-philadelphia-2017/|url-status=live}}</ref> Eilish released "[[Bitches Broken Hearts]]" through SoundCloud on November 10, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/billieeilish/bitches-broken-hearts|title=bitches broken hearts by Billie Eilish|publisher=[[SoundCloud]]|access-date=June 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200518042055/https://soundcloud.com/billieeilish/bitches-broken-hearts|archive-date=May 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="dork">{{cite web|url=https://www.readdork.com/news/billie-eilish-has-shared-a-surprise-new-single-bitches-broken-hearts|title=Billie Eilish has shared a surprise new single 'Bitches Broken Hearts'|website=[[Dork (magazine)|Dork]]|access-date=June 24, 2020|date=November 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200628203059/https://www.readdork.com/news/billie-eilish-has-shared-a-surprise-new-single-bitches-broken-hearts|archive-date=June 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Fit">{{cite web|url=https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/new-music/discovery/billie-eilish-debuts-raw-rb-charmer-bitches-broken-hearts|title=Billie Eilish debuts raw R&B charmer 'Bitches Broken Hearts'|last=Day|first=Laurnce|website=[[The Line of Best Fit]]|access-date=June 24, 2020|date=November 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200629074647/https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/new-music/discovery/billie-eilish-debuts-raw-rb-charmer-bitches-broken-hearts|archive-date=June 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2017/11/billie-eilish-bitches-broken-hearts|title=Billie Eilish Releases Surprise Single 'Bitches Broken Hearts'|last=Moore|first=Jacob|website=[[Complex Networks (company)|Complex]]|access-date=June 24, 2020|date=November 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200628080422/https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2017/11/billie-eilish-bitches-broken-hearts|archive-date=June 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>

Eilish's team worked with [[Spotify]], which promoted her on its most popular playlist, "Today's Top Hits".<ref name="Buzz"/> ''[[The Baffler]]'' described Eilish's sound as fitting into the "streambait" genre consisting of largely "mid-tempo, melancholy pop" influenced by [[Lana Del Rey]], whose "singing style, bleakness, and... hip-hop influenced production" shaped the aesthetic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thebaffler.com/downstream/streambait-pop-pelly|title=Streambait Pop|first=Liz|last=Pelly|work=[[The Baffler]]|date=December 11, 2018|access-date=January 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127081650/https://thebaffler.com/downstream/streambait-pop-pelly|archive-date=January 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Buzz"/> Eilish's commercial success expanded with her Spotify promotion.<ref name="Buzz"/> In September 2017, Apple Music named Eilish their [[Apple Music Up Next|Up Next]] artist, which followed with a short documentary, a live session EP, and an interview with [[Zane Lowe]] on Apple Music's radio station [[Beats 1]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Stubblebine|first1=Allison|title=Billie Eilish Is Apple's New UpNext Artist: Exclusive|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7972832/apple-upnext-artist-billie-eilish-video|magazine=Billboard|date=September 20, 2017|access-date=February 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207235346/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7972832/apple-upnext-artist-billie-eilish-video|archive-date=February 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> That month, the live EP, ''[[Up Next Session: Billie Eilish]]'', was released. On December 15, 2017, Eilish released her collaboration with American rapper [[Vince Staples]], "[[&Burn]]", a remix of her single "Watch". It was included on the expanded edition of ''Don't Smile at Me''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Minsker|first=Evan|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/billie-eilish-enlists-vince-staples-for-new-song-andburn-listen/|title=Billie Eilish Enlists Vince Staples for New Song "&burn": Listen|work=Pitchfork|date=December 14, 2017|access-date=January 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128144628/https://pitchfork.com/news/billie-eilish-enlists-vince-staples-for-new-song-andburn-listen/|archive-date=January 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="variance">{{cite web|url=https://variancemagazine.com/sounds/8745-billie-eilish-burn-featuring-vince-staples|title=Hear Billie Eilish's Simmering New Track '&Burn,' Featuring Vince Staples|last=Howard|first=Lindsay|date=December 14, 2017|work=[[Variance (magazine)|Variance]]|access-date=July 30, 2020|archive-date=September 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200913195143/https://variancemagazine.com/sounds/8745-billie-eilish-burn-featuring-vince-staples|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8070739/billie-eilish-new-song-burn-vince-staples/|title=Billie Eilish Unveils New Track 'Burn' Featuring Vince Staples, Whose Verse Is 'So Mf Good'|last=Hussein|first=Wandera|date=December 15, 2017|magazine=Billboard|access-date=July 30, 2020|archive-date=October 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201001063155/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8070739/billie-eilish-new-song-burn-vince-staples|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billieeilish.com/music/dont-smile-me|title=dont smile at me|publisher=Billie Eilish|access-date=June 19, 2020|archive-date=June 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200621200107/https://www.billieeilish.com/music/dont-smile-me|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== 2018–2020: ''When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?'' ===
{{Main|When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?}}

In February 2018, Eilish embarked on her second headlining concert tour, the [[Where's My Mind Tour]], which concluded in April 2018.<ref name="broad2">{{cite web|last=Kfare|first=Danielle|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/-Billie-Eilish-Tour-Adds-Second-NYC-Date-And-Upgrades-Boston-Venue-20171208|title=Billie Eilish Tour Adds Second NYC Date And Upgrades Boston Venue|publisher=[[BroadwayWorld]]|date=December 8, 2017|access-date=September 16, 2020|archive-date=October 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201001063233/https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/-Billie-Eilish-Tour-Adds-Second-NYC-Date-And-Upgrades-Boston-Venue-20171208|url-status=live}}</ref> "Bitches Broken Hearts" was re-released worldwide on March 30, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umusic.ca/press-releases/billie-eilish-officially-releases-bitches-broken-hearts-fans/|title=Billie Eilish Officially Releases 'bitches broken hearts' for Fans|publisher=Universal Music Group|access-date=June 22, 2020|archive-date=October 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201001063219/http://www.umusic.ca/press-releases/billie-eilish-officially-releases-bitches-broken-hearts-fans/|url-status=live}}</ref> For [[Record Store Day]] 2018, Eilish released "[[Party Favor (song)|Party Favor]]" on a pink [[7-inch|7-inch vinyl]], along with a cover of "[[Hotline Bling]]", by [[Drake (musician)|Drake]], as the B-side.<ref name="RecordStoreDay">{{cite web|title=Party Favor/Hot Line Bling [Pink Vinyl Single]|url=https://recordstoreday.com/UPC/602567383659|publisher=[[Record Store Day]]|date=April 24, 2018|access-date=April 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420060948/https://recordstoreday.com/UPC/602567383659|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Eilish collaborated with American singer [[Khalid (singer)|Khalid]] on the single "[[Lovely (Billie Eilish and Khalid song)|Lovely]]", which was released on April 19, 2018, and added to the soundtrack for the second season of ''13 Reasons Why''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/lovely-single/1369379667|title=Lovely by Billie Eilish and Khalid on iTunes|publisher=iTunes|access-date=April 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605151741/https://music.apple.com/us/album/lovely-single/1369379667|archive-date=June 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She released "[[You Should See Me in a Crown]]" in July 2018,<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Whittum |first=Connor |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8466045/billie-eilish-you-should-see-me-in-a-crown |title= Billie Eilish Drops Dramatic Track 'You Should See Me in a Crown': Listen |magazine= Billboard |date=July 18, 2018 |access-date=July 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719015549/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8466045/billie-eilish-you-should-see-me-in-a-crown |archive-date=July 19, 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref> The same month, Eilish performed at the [[Mo Pop Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mo Pop Festival: 2018 lineup & tix (Bon Iver, The National, St. Vincent, more) |url=http://www.brooklynvegan.com/mo-pop-festival-2018-lineup-tix-bon-iver-the-national-st-vincent-more/ |website=BrooklynVegan |date=March 7, 2018 |access-date=June 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517093207/http://www.brooklynvegan.com/mo-pop-festival-2018-lineup-tix-bon-iver-the-national-st-vincent-more/ |archive-date=May 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[File:Billie Eilish at Pukkelpop Festival - 18 AUGUST 2019 (01) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Eilish at Pukkelpop Festival in 2019]]
On the day of release for her single "[[When the Party's Over (song)|When the Party's Over]]",<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Engelman|first=Nicole|title=Billie Eilish Releases Haunting New Song 'When The Party's Over': Listen|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8480413/billie-eilish-when-the-partys-over|magazine=Billboard|access-date=October 18, 2018|date=October 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018170223/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8480413/billie-eilish-when-the-partys-over|archive-date=October 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Eilish was featured in [[Vanity Fair (magazine)|''Vanity Fair''{{'}}s]] "73 Questions" rapid-fire questionnaire video series by [[Joe Sabia]], who revisited an interview from October 2017. The resulting video was a side-by-side [[time capsule]] of both interviews showing her growth in popularity over one year.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kennedy |first=Joan |date=December 24, 2018 |title=The Sabia Effect |url=https://magazine.bcheights.com/index.php/2018/the-sabia-effect/ |access-date=August 8, 2020 |newspaper=[[The Heights (newspaper)|The Heights]] |archive-date=August 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200815050004/https://magazine.bcheights.com/index.php/2018/the-sabia-effect/ |url-status=live }}</ref> She signed a talent contract with [[Next Management]] for fashion and beauty endorsements in October 2018.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Patel |first1=Shyam |title=Billie Eilish Just Got Signed to a Major Modeling Agency |url=http://www.papermag.com/billie-eilish-next-models-1-2614833635.html |magazine=Paper |access-date=May 27, 2019 |date=October 24, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190527053429/http://www.papermag.com/billie-eilish-next-models-1-2614833635.html |archive-date=May 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nextmanagement.com/los-angeles/profile/billie-eilish|title=Billie Eilish|publisher=Next Management|access-date=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415102916/https://www.nextmanagement.com/los-angeles/profile/billie-eilish|archive-date=April 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She was placed on the 2018 [[Forbes 30 Under 30]] list in November of that year,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shaw |first1=Syd |title=Billie Eilish, Timothée Chalamet & 21 Savage Lead Forbes Eclectic "30 Under 30" |url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2018/11/216876/30-under-30-billie-eilish-timothee-chalamet |publisher=[[Refinery 29]] |date=November 13, 2018|access-date=June 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605171412/https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2018/11/216876/30-under-30-billie-eilish-timothee-chalamet |archive-date=June 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Greenburg |first1=Zack O'Malley |title=Meet Billie Eilish, The 30 Under 30 Music Sensation Poised To Pop |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2018/11/15/meet-billie-eilish-the-30-under-30-music-sensation-poised-to-pop/#513bda6e7150 |magazine=[[Forbes]] |date=November 15, 2018|access-date=June 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605171414/https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2018/11/15/meet-billie-eilish-the-30-under-30-music-sensation-poised-to-pop/#513bda6e7150 |archive-date=June 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and released the single "[[Come Out and Play (Billie Eilish song)|Come Out and Play]]" in November 2018, which was written for a holiday-themed [[Apple Inc.]] commercial.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Moore |first1=Sam |title=Listen to Billie Eilish's heartfelt new single 'come out and play' |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/billie-eilish-come-out-and-play-single-2404757 |magazine=[[NME]] |access-date=June 5, 2019 |date=November 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228174900/https://www.nme.com/news/music/billie-eilish-come-out-and-play-single-2404757 |archive-date=December 28, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In early January 2019, ''Don't Smile at Me'' reached 1&nbsp;billion streams on Spotify, making her the youngest artist to top 1&nbsp;billion streams on a project.<ref name="Buzz" /> That month, Eilish released "[[Bury a Friend]]" as the third single from her debut album ''[[When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?]]'',<ref name="Rowden-2019">{{cite web|first=Claire|last=Rowden|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/billie-eilish/news/billie-eilish-just-released-a-teaser-for-new-music-and-were-so-ready-for-it|title=Billie Eilish Just Released A Teaser For New Music And We're So Ready For It|publisher=[[MTV (British and Irish TV channel)|MTV]]|date=January 29, 2019|access-date=January 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329172657/http://www.mtv.co.uk/billie-eilish/news/billie-eilish-just-released-a-teaser-for-new-music-and-were-so-ready-for-it|archive-date=March 29, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="Maicki-2019">{{cite magazine|last=Maicki|first=Salvatore|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/01/28/billie-eilish-new-single-trailer|title=Watch a trailer for new music from Billie Eilish|magazine=The Fader|date=January 28, 2019|access-date=January 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190130053446/https://www.thefader.com/2019/01/28/billie-eilish-new-single-trailer|archive-date=January 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> along with "[[When I Was Older]]", a single inspired by the 2018 film [[Roma (2018 film)|''Roma'']], which appeared on the compilation album ''Music Inspired by the Film Roma''.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Acevedo |first1=Angelica |title=Billie Eilish Unleashes New Song 'When I Was Older (Inspired By Roma)': Listen |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8492849/billie-eilish-when-i-was-older-roma |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=January 9, 2019|access-date=June 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190611112919/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8492849/billie-eilish-when-i-was-older-roma |archive-date=June 11, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Kreps |first1=Daniel |title=Hear Billie Eilish's 'Roma'-Inspired Ballad 'When I Was Older' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/billie-eilish-roma-song-776772/ |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|url-access=limited |access-date=June 5, 2019 |date=January 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605180412/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/billie-eilish-roma-song-776772/ |archive-date=June 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In February, Eilish partnered with YouTube on a documentary miniseries, "A Snippet Into Billie's Mind".<ref name="mn" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://alt1037dfw.radio.com/blogs/jenn/billie-eilish-bury-friend-youtube-documentary|title=Billie Eilish Reveals 'A Snippet Into Billie's Mind' Mini-Series. Episode One: "Bury a Friend"|publisher=[[KVIL]]|date=February 27, 2019|access-date=January 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129024645/https://alt1037dfw.radio.com/blogs/jenn/billie-eilish-bury-friend-youtube-documentary|archive-date=January 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> "[[Wish You Were Gay]]", her fourth single from the album, was released on March 4, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|first=Stephen|last=Daw
|date=March 4, 2019|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8500854/billie-eilish-wish-you-were-gay|title=Billie Eilish Is Tired Of Heartache On New Single 'Wish You Were Gay': Listen|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=March 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305035759/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8500854/billie-eilish-wish-you-were-gay|archive-date=March 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

''When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?'' was released on March 29, 2019.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Exposito |first1=Suzy |title=Review: Billie Eilish's 'When We All Sleep, Where Do We Go?' is Noir Pop With Bite |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/review-billie-eilish-when-we-all-sleep-where-do-we-go-814754/ |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|url-access=limited|access-date=March 29, 2019 |date=March 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329182510/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/review-billie-eilish-when-we-all-sleep-where-do-we-go-814754/ |archive-date=March 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Spotify launched a "multi-level campaign behind the album", creating a multimedia playlist and "new product features" that Spotify said "allow for vertical video content, custom assets, and editorial storylines, all with the goal of creating more meaningful and engaging context for [Eilish's] fans."<ref name="mn"/> In Los Angeles, Spotify set up a "pop-up enhanced album experience", which included different artwork and a "multi-sensory" experience of each track for fans.<ref name="mn">{{cite magazine|url=https://themusicnetwork.com/becoming-billie-how-apple-music-and-spotify-helped-make-billie-eilish-musics-new-gen-z-superstar/|title=Becoming Billie: How Apple Music and Spotify helped make Billie Eilish music's new Gen Z superstar|magazine=[[The Music Network]]|date=April 1, 2019|access-date=January 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225234101/https://themusicnetwork.com/becoming-billie-how-apple-music-and-spotify-helped-make-billie-eilish-musics-new-gen-z-superstar/|archive-date=February 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The album debuted atop the ''[[Billboard 200]]'' as well as on the [[UK Albums Chart]], making Eilish the first artist born in the 2000s to have a number-one album in the U.S. and the youngest female ever to have a number-one album in the United Kingdom.<ref name="Trammell"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Ainsley|first=Helen|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/billie-eilish-holds-on-to-number-1-on-the-official-albums-chart-as-khalid-scores-highest-new-entry__26062/|title=Official Albums Chart: Billie Eilish holds on to Number 1|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=April 12, 2019|access-date=May 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412160347/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/billie-eilish-holds-on-to-number-1-on-the-official-albums-chart-as-khalid-scores-highest-new-entry__26062/|archive-date=April 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Upon the album's debut, Eilish broke the record for most simultaneously charting Hot 100 songs by a female artist, with 14, after every song from the album, excluding "Goodbye", charted on the Hot 100.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Zellner |first1=Xander |title=Billie Eilish Earns First Hot 100 Top 10, Breaks Record For Most Simultaneous Hits Among Women |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8506406/billie-eilish-earns-first-hot-100-top-10 |magazine=Billboard |date=April 9, 2019 |access-date=May 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422164844/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8506406/billie-eilish-earns-first-hot-100-top-10 |archive-date=April 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The fifth single from the album, "[[Bad Guy (Billie Eilish song)|Bad Guy]]", was released in conjunction with the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uproxx.com/music/lil-nas-x-congratulates-billie-eilish/|title=Lil Nas X Congratulates Billie Eilish On 'Bad Guy' Hitting No. 1 On The Hot 100 Chart|last1=Williams|first1=Aaron|date=August 19, 2019|website=[[Uproxx]]|access-date=August 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819221504/https://uproxx.com/music/lil-nas-x-congratulates-billie-eilish/|archive-date=August 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A remix of the song featuring [[Justin Bieber]] was released in July 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Roth |first1=Madeline |title=It's Here: Billie Eilish And Justin Bieber Are 'Bad Guys' On New Collab |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3130980/billie-eilish-justin-bieber-bad-guy/ |agency=MTV News |access-date=August 8, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808041153/http://www.mtv.com/news/3130980/billie-eilish-justin-bieber-bad-guy/ |archive-date=August 8, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Murphy |first1=Rhodes |title=Bilie Eilish and Lil Nas X Are Trying to Remix Their Way to No. 1 |url=https://slate.com/culture/2019/07/lil-nas-x-is-billie-eilishs-enemy-number-one-in-a-billboard-remix-war.html |magazine=Slate |access-date=August 8, 2019 |date=July 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808041153/https://slate.com/culture/2019/07/lil-nas-x-is-billie-eilishs-enemy-number-one-in-a-billboard-remix-war.html |archive-date=August 8, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In August, Bad Guy peaked at number-one in the US, ending [[Lil Nas X]]'s record-breaking [[List of Billboard Hot 100 chart achievements and milestones#Most weeks at No. 1 on the Billboard Hot 100|19 weeks]] at number-one with "[[Old Town Road]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/billie-eilish-scores-first-no-1-single-ending-old-town-roads-19-week-run/|title=Billie Eilish Scores First No. 1 Single, Ending "Old Town Road"'s 19-Week Run|last1=Bloom|first1=Madison|last2=Kim|first2=Michelle|website=[[Pitchfork (magazine)|Pitchfork]]|date=August 19, 2019|access-date=August 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819221504/https://pitchfork.com/news/billie-eilish-scores-first-no-1-single-ending-old-town-roads-19-week-run/|archive-date=August 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She is the first artist born in the 2000s and the youngest artist since [[Lorde]] (with "[[Royals (Lorde song)|Royals]]") to have a number-one single.<ref name="sgn1">{{cite web |last1=Breihan |first1=Tom |title=Billie Eilish's "Bad Guy" Has Finally Dethroned Lil Nas X's "Old Town Road" At #1 |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2055270/billie-eilishs-bad-guy-has-finally-dethroned-lil-nas-xs-old-town-road-at-1/news/ |website=[[Stereogum]] |access-date=August 19, 2019 |date=August 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819221505/https://www.stereogum.com/2055270/billie-eilishs-bad-guy-has-finally-dethroned-lil-nas-xs-old-town-road-at-1/news/ |archive-date=August 19, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[File:ALTer EGO 1 18 2020 (50740920597) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Eilish (left) in 2020 with her brother and collaborator [[Finneas O'Connell]]]]
Eilish began her [[When We All Fall Asleep Tour]] at [[Coachella Valley Music & Arts Festival|Coachella Festival]] in April 2019,<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Nesvig |first1=Kara |title=Billie Eilish Forgot Her Own Lyrics at Coachella But It Only Made Fans Love Her More |url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/billie-eilish-lyrics-coachella-2019 |magazine=[[Teen Vogue]] |date=April 15, 2019|access-date=August 8, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418180832/https://www.teenvogue.com/story/billie-eilish-lyrics-coachella-2019 |archive-date=April 18, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> with the tour concluding on November 17, 2019, in [[Mexico City]]. In August 2019, she partnered with Apple Music for Music Lab: Remix Billie Eilish, part of [[Apple Stores]]' Music Lab sessions during which fans deconstruct her song "You Should See Me In A Crown" and learn how to create their own remix on Apple devices and [[GarageBand]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://themusicnetwork.com/australians-to-remix-billie-eilish/|title=Australians first to remix Billie Eilish with Apple Music Labs|date=August 5, 2019|access-date=January 28, 2020|magazine=[[The Music Network]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129052328/https://themusicnetwork.com/australians-to-remix-billie-eilish/|archive-date=January 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hartshorn|first=Tori|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Billie-Eilish-and-Apple-Announce-Music-Lab-Remix-Billie-Eilish-20190801|title=Billie Eilish and Apple Announce Music Lab: Remix Billie Eilish|publisher=[[BroadwayWorld]]|date=August 1, 2019|access-date=January 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129052329/https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Billie-Eilish-and-Apple-Announce-Music-Lab-Remix-Billie-Eilish-20190801|archive-date=January 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 27, 2019, Eilish announced her [[Where Do We Go? World Tour]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Asmelash|first=Leah|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/27/us/billie-eilish-where-do-we-go-world-tour-trnd/index.html|title=Billie Eilish just announced another world tour|agency=CNN|date=September 28, 2019|access-date=December 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226171208/https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/27/us/billie-eilish-where-do-we-go-world-tour-trnd/index.html|archive-date=December 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The tour began in Miami on March 9, 2020, and ran for two more shows on March 10 in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]] and March 12 in [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]] before Eilish ended the tour prematurely due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]]. The tour was set to conclude in [[Jakarta]] on September 7.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=December 4, 2020 |title=Billie Eilish cancels her 'When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?' world tour |url=https://www.nme.com/en_asia/news/music/billie-eilish-cancels-her-when-we-all-fall-asleep-where-do-we-go-world-tour-2831849 |access-date=December 4, 2020 |magazine=NME |archive-date=December 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201205062047/https://www.nme.com/en_asia/news/music/billie-eilish-cancels-her-when-we-all-fall-asleep-where-do-we-go-world-tour-2831849 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On November 7, 2019, [[Jack White]]'s [[Third Man Records]] announced that the label would release an acoustic live album of Eilish's performance from the record label's Blue Room, exclusively sold on vinyl at Third Man retail locations in [[Nashville]], [[Tennessee]], and Detroit, Michigan.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Burks|first=Tosten|url=https://www.spin.com/2019/11/billie-eilish-jack-white-live-album/|title=Jack White's Third Man Records Announces Billie Eilish Live Album|magazine=Spin|date=November 7, 2019|access-date=November 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112091723/https://www.spin.com/2019/11/billie-eilish-jack-white-live-album/|archive-date=November 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On November 13, 2019, she released her next single, "[[Everything I Wanted (Billie Eilish song)|Everything I Wanted]]".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://genius.com/Billie-eilish-everything-i-wanted-lyrics|title=Billie Eilish – Everything I Wanted Genius Lyrics|publisher=Genius|date=November 13, 2019|access-date=November 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116203605/https://genius.com/Billie-eilish-everything-i-wanted-lyrics|archive-date=November 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On November 20, 2019, Eilish was nominated for six [[Grammy Awards]], including [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] for "[[Bad Guy (Billie Eilish song)|Bad Guy]]" as well as [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]]. At age 17, she became the youngest artist to be nominated in [[Big Four (Grammy Awards)|all four General Field categories]].<ref name="Warner-2019">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8544267/2020-grammy-nominations-complete-list|title=2020 Grammy Nominees: The Complete List|last=Warner|first=Denise|date=November 20, 2019|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url-status=live|access-date=November 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120200318/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8544267/2020-grammy-nominations-complete-list|archive-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref> In the same month, Eilish was crowned 2019's [[Billboard Women in Music#Woman of the Year Award|''Billboard'' Woman of the Year]].<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8544457/billie-eilish-billboard-2019-woman-of-the-year|title=Billie Eilish Is Billboard's 2019 Woman of the Year|last=Mamo|first=Heran|date=November 25, 2019|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url-status=live|access-date=November 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191126051603/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8544457/billie-eilish-billboard-2019-woman-of-the-year|archive-date=November 26, 2019}}</ref>

[[File:ALTer EGO 1 18 2020 (50740816801).jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|left|Eilish at the ALTer EGO concert in January 2020]]
On January 14, 2020, Eilish was announced as performer of the [[No Time to Die (song)|title track]] for the 25th installment in the [[List of James Bond films|James Bond film franchise]], ''[[No Time to Die]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/jan/14/james-bond-billie-eilish-to-provide-no-time-to-die-theme|title=James Bond: Billie Eilish to provide No Time to Die theme|last=Snapes|first=Laura|date=January 14, 2020|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=January 14, 2020|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114175857/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/jan/14/james-bond-billie-eilish-to-provide-no-time-to-die-theme|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> written and produced with her brother. With this announcement, Eilish became the youngest artist to write and perform a James Bond theme song.<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Aniftos|first=Rania|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8550873/billie-eilish-no-time-to-die-release-date|title=Billie Eilish's James Bond Theme, 'No Time to Die,' Gets a Release Date|magazine=Billboard|date=February 12, 2020|access-date=February 17, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213000721/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8550873/billie-eilish-no-time-to-die-release-date|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It became the second Bond theme song to top the British official charts and the first Bond theme performed by a female artist to do so. It was also Eilish's first number-one single in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|last=Copsey|first=Rob|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/billie-eilishs-no-time-to-die-scores-biggest-opening-week-of-all-time-for-a-james-bond-theme__28767/|title=Billie Eilish scores biggest opening week of all time for a Bond theme|publisher=Official Charts Company|date=February 21, 2020|access-date=February 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221181653/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/billie-eilishs-no-time-to-die-scores-biggest-opening-week-of-all-time-for-a-james-bond-theme__28767/|archive-date=February 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[62nd Grammy Awards]], she became the youngest person to win the four main Grammy categories – [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]], [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]], and [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] – in the same year.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8544181/artists-nominated-big-4-categories-grammy-awards|title=Grammy Awards: All the Artists Who've Been Nominated in the Big 4 Categories in the Same Year|last=Grein|first=Paul|date=November 20, 2019|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=November 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120204718/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8544181/artists-nominated-big-4-categories-grammy-awards|archive-date=November 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/27/entertainment/billie-eilish-grammys/index.html|title=Billie Eilish has a history-making night at the Grammys|last=Gonzalez|first=Sandra|date=January 26, 2020|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127051943/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/27/entertainment/billie-eilish-grammys/index.html|archive-date=January 27, 2020|access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref> During the COVID-19 pandemic, Eilish and her brother performed for both [[iHeart Media]]'s Living Room Concert for America,<ref name="LivingRoom">{{cite web|first=Daniel|last=D'Addario|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/fox-iheart-living-room-concert-for-america-tv-review-1203548417/|title=Fox's 'iHeart Living Room Concert for America': TV Review|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 29, 2020|access-date=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331021256/https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/fox-iheart-living-room-concert-for-america-tv-review-1203548417/|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Global Citizen (website)|Global Citizen]]'s [[Together at Home]] concert series, singing a cover of [[Bobby Hebb]]'s [[Sunny (Bobby Hebb song)|"Sunny"]] for the latter.<ref name="Sunny">{{cite AV media |title=Billie Eilish & Finneas perform "Sunny" {{!}} One World: Together At Home |via=YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IJuHn8JzhP0|access-date=April 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420042302/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IJuHn8JzhP0|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Both virtual concerts were an effort to raise awareness and funds towards fighting the disease.<ref name="LivingRoom" /><ref name="Sunny" /> On April 10, 2020, "[[Ilomilo (song)|Ilomilo]]" was sent to Italian [[contemporary hit radio]] stations by [[Universal Music Group]], as ''When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?''{{'}}s seventh and final single.<ref name="radio">{{cite news|url=http://radiodate.it/radio-date/billie-eilish-ilomilo-200412-10-04-2020-radiodate/|title=Billie Eilish – "Ilomilo" {{!}} (Radio Date: April 10, 2020)|publisher=Radiodate.it|access-date=May 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200515092826/http://radiodate.it/radio-date/billie-eilish-ilomilo-200412-10-04-2020-radiodate/|archive-date=May 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On July 30, 2020, Eilish released "[[My Future]]", her first original release since "No Time to Die", along with an animated video.<ref>{{cite web |last=Langford |first=Jackson |date=July 30, 2020 |title=Listen to Billie Eilish's stunning new single 'My Future' |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/listen-to-billie-eilishs-stunning-new-single-my-future-2718749 |access-date=August 8, 2020 |website=[[NME]] |archive-date=August 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200806191404/https://www.nme.com/news/music/listen-to-billie-eilishs-stunning-new-single-my-future-2718749 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2020, she became the youngest person to feature on the [[Forbes Celebrity 100|''Forbes'' Celebrity 100]] list, with earnings of $53&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=#43: Billie Eilish|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/billie-eilish/?list=celebrities#65e90257610c|url-status=live|access-date=June 26, 2020|magazine=[[Forbes]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200627223324/https://www.forbes.com/profile/billie-eilish/?list=celebrities#65e90257610c|archive-date=June 27, 2020}}</ref> In September 2020, Eilish released a collection of branded ukuleles with guitar manufacturer [[Fender (brand)|Fender]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9445798/billie-eilish-fender-signature-ukulele|title=Billie Eilish Teams With Fender For a Signature Ukulele|magazine=Billboard|date=September 8, 2020|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|access-date=October 16, 2021|archive-date=October 17, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211017010650/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9445798/billie-eilish-fender-signature-ukulele|url-status=live}}</ref>

In October 2020, Eilish announced a livestream concert titled ''Where Do We Go? The Livestream'' set to air from Los Angeles on October 24, with proceeds from the show's merchandise raising funds to support event crew members affected by the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Aniftos |first1=Rania |title=Billie Eilish Announces Global 'Where Do We Go?' Livestream Concert |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9461986/billie-eilish-global-livestream-concert/ |magazine=Billboard |access-date=October 7, 2020 |date=October 7, 2020 |archive-date=October 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201007222315/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9461986/billie-eilish-global-livestream-concert/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In a ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' interview, Eilish said she was working on "sixteen new songs and lov[ing] them all", revealing an upcoming musical project.<ref>{{cite interview|last=Eilish|first=Billie|title=Billie Eilish: Same Interview, The Fourth Year|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/video/watch/same-interview-one-year-apart-billie-eilish-same-interview-the-fourth-year|access-date=December 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201212105208/https://www.vanityfair.com/video/watch/same-interview-one-year-apart-billie-eilish-same-interview-the-fourth-year|archive-date=December 12, 2020|url-status=live|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date=October 18, 2020|interviewer-last=Sabia|interviewer-first=Joe|url-access=limited}}</ref> Eilish won three [[Billboard Music Award|''Billboard'' Music Awards]] on October 24—[[Billboard Music Award for Top Female Artist|''Billboard'' Music Award for Top Female Artist]], [[Billboard Music Award for Top Billboard 200 Album|''Billboard'' Music Award for Top ''Billboard'' 200 Album]] (''When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?''), and [[Billboard Music Award for Top New Artist|''Billboard'' Music Award for Top New Artist]]—out of the 12 that she was nominated for. Also that month, she announced a new single, "[[Therefore I Am (song)|Therefore I Am]]", which was released along with its video on November 12, 2020.<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Aniftos|first=Rania|date=November 9, 2020|title=Billie Eilish Is Dropping a New Single in Just Days|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9480846/billie-eilish-announces-therefore-i-am/|access-date=November 10, 2020|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|archive-date=November 9, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201109225536/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9480846/billie-eilish-announces-therefore-i-am|url-status=live}}</ref> Eilish performed "Therefore I Am" and "My Future" at the [[Jingle Ball]] in December 2020.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Richards |first1=Will |title=Watch Billie Eilish deliver a festive rendition of 'Silver Bells' |url=https://www.nme.com/en_asia/news/music/watch-billie-eilish-deliver-a-festive-rendition-of-silver-bells-2837458 |access-date=December 16, 2020 |magazine=NME |date=December 11, 2020 |archive-date=April 1, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210401025543/https://www.nme.com/en_asia/news/music/watch-billie-eilish-deliver-a-festive-rendition-of-silver-bells-2837458 |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== 2021–2023: ''Happier Than Ever'' and ''Guitar Songs'' ===
{{Main|Happier Than Ever|Guitar Songs}}
[[File:Billie Eilish at the 2021 Met Gala - 01.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.9|Eilish at the 2021 [[Met Gala]]]]

"[[Lo Vas a Olvidar]]", a single featuring [[Rosalía (singer)|Rosalía]] as a part of [[HBO]]'s ''[[Euphoria (American TV series)|Euphoria]]'' soundtrack, was released in January 2021, almost two years after initially teasing the song.<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Flores|first=Griselda|date=January 19, 2021|title=Billie Eilish and Rosalía's Highly-Anticipated Collab 'Lo Vas a Olvidar' Is Dropping This Week|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9513330/billie-eilish-rosalia-lo-vas-a-olvidar-euphoria-new-song-teaser|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210125160511/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9513330/billie-eilish-rosalia-lo-vas-a-olvidar-euphoria-new-song-teaser/|archive-date=January 25, 2021|access-date=|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> The [[R. J. Cutler]]–directed documentary film ''[[Billie Eilish: The World's a Little Blurry]]'' was released on Apple TV+ and in select movie theaters. The film was praised by critics and fans for its in-depth look at Eilish's personal life during her ascent to fame.<ref>{{cite web|title=Billie Eilish: The World's a Little Blurry|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/billie_eilish_the_worlds_a_little_blurry|url-status=live|access-date=February 28, 2021|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|date=February 26, 2021 |archive-date=February 27, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210227050621/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/billie_eilish_the_worlds_a_little_blurry}}</ref> At the [[63rd Annual Grammy Awards]], Eilish took home two awards: the [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media]] for her [[No Time to Die (song)|Bond theme]] and the [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year]] for "[[Everything I Wanted]]". In her acceptance speech for Record of the Year, Eilish said that [[Megan Thee Stallion]] "deserved to win", but still thanked her fans and her brother for her award.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Mier|first1=Tomás|last2=Rice|first2=Nicholas|title=Billie Eilish Wins Record of the Year at 2021 Grammys — but Says Megan Thee Stallion Deserved It|url=https://people.com/music/grammys-2021-billie-eilish-wins-record-of-the-year/|url-status=live|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=March 15, 2021|access-date=March 30, 2021|archive-date=March 16, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210316090606/https://people.com/music/grammys-2021-billie-eilish-wins-record-of-the-year/}}</ref>

2021 saw the publication of her personally selected comprehensive book of photographs that shared "an intimate window into her life" on and off stage, ''By - Billie Eilish.''<ref>{{Cite web |title=By --- Billie Eilish |url=https://www.waterstones.com/book/billie-eilish/billie-eilish/9781526364104 |access-date=December 9, 2023 |archive-date=December 9, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231209045558/https://www.waterstones.com/book/billie-eilish/billie-eilish/9781526364104 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On April 27, 2021, Eilish announced on her [[Instagram]] account that her second album, ''[[Happier Than Ever]]'', would be released on July 30, and the tracklist was made available on Apple Music. The album was released in various formats, including collectible vinyl and cassette colors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://shopuk.billieeilish.com/*/*/-Happier-Than-Ever-Exclusive-Vinyl-Bundle/6YRQ0000000 |title='Happier Than Ever' Exclusive Vinyl Bundle|publisher= Billie Eilish Official Store |access-date=April 27, 2021 |archive-date=April 28, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210428002223/https://shopuk.billieeilish.com/%2A/%2A/-Happier-Than-Ever-Exclusive-Vinyl-Bundle/6YRQ0000000 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://shopuk.billieeilish.com/*/*/-Happier-Than-Ever-CD-Exclusive-Pink-Cassette-Exclusive-Brown-Cassette/6YRR0000000 |title=Happier Than Ever' CD + Exclusive Pink Cassette + Exclusive Brown Cassette |publisher=Billie Eilish Official Store |access-date=April 27, 2021 |archive-date=April 28, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210428002233/https://shopuk.billieeilish.com/%2A/%2A/-Happier-Than-Ever-CD-Exclusive-Pink-Cassette-Exclusive-Brown-Cassette/6YRR0000000 |url-status=live}}</ref> The album's release was preceded by five singles: "My Future", "Therefore I Am", "[[Your Power]]",<ref>{{cite web |last=Todisco |first=Eric |url=https://people.com/music/billie-eilish-releases-music-video-new-single-your-power/ |title=Billie Eilish Drops Music Video to New Single 'Your Power' from Upcoming Second Album |website=PEOPLE.com |date=April 29, 2021 |access-date=May 3, 2021 |archive-date=May 3, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210503064226/https://people.com/music/billie-eilish-releases-music-video-new-single-your-power/ |url-status=live}}</ref> "[[Lost Cause (Billie Eilish song)|Lost Cause]]",<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=Billie Eilish Announces Her Next Single 'Lost Cause' & Music Video {{!}} Billboard News|url=https://www.billboard.com/video/billie-eilish-announces-her-next-single-lost-cause-music-video-billboard-news|access-date=July 12, 2021 |magazine=Billboard|archive-date=June 1, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210601183146/https://www.billboard.com/video/billie-eilish-announces-her-next-single-lost-cause-music-video-billboard-news|url-status=live}}</ref> and "[[NDA (song)|NDA]]",<ref>{{cite magazine|date=July 9, 2021|first=Nicholas|last=Rice|title=Billie Eilish Releases Self-Directed Music Video for New Single 'NDA' from Forthcoming Album|url=https://people.com/music/billie-eilish-releases-music-video-nda/|access-date=July 10, 2021 |magazine=People|archive-date=July 12, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210712205552/https://people.com/music/billie-eilish-releases-music-video-nda/|url-status=live}}</ref> and was accompanied by [[Happier Than Ever (song)|the title track]]. On December 2, 2021, Eilish announced an eco-friendly limited-edition vinyl version of ''Happier Than Ever'' made from recycled vinyl scraps. The collector's item was available only at a number of Gucci stores around the world and included Gucci-branded nail stickers designed by the brand's creative director, Alessandro Michele.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|title=Billie Eilish Teams Up With Gucci For Limited-Edition 'Happier Than Ever' Recycled Vinyl|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/billie-eilish-gucci-limited-edition-happier-than-ever-vinyl-1235005483/|date=December 3, 2021|access-date=December 3, 2021|magazine=Billboard|archive-date=December 3, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211203142424/https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/billie-eilish-gucci-limited-edition-happier-than-ever-vinyl-1235005483/|url-status=live}}</ref> To further promote the album, Eilish worked with [[Disney+]] on the concert film ''[[Happier Than Ever: A Love Letter to Los Angeles]]'', released in September 2021,<ref name="ConcertFilm">{{Cite magazine |last=Gardner |first=Chris |date=August 30, 2021 |title='It's Scary and Mean out There': Billie Eilish on Ignoring Internet Comments amid ''Happier Than Ever'' Success |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/music-news/billie-eilish-disney-special-happier-than-ever-1235003818/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220407120357/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/music-news/billie-eilish-disney-special-happier-than-ever-1235003818/ |archive-date=April 7, 2022 |access-date=August 1, 2022 |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref><ref name="BillboardReview">{{Cite magazine |last=Urbanek |first=Sydney |date=September 7, 2021 |title=Billie Eilish Relearns Her Hometown and Herself in Disney+ Film ''Happier Than Ever: A Love Letter to Los Angeles'' |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/billie-eilish-happier-than-ever-disney-plus-review-9625691/ |url-status=live |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220705190756/https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/billie-eilish-happier-than-ever-disney-plus-review-9625691/ |archive-date=July 5, 2022 |access-date=August 1, 2022}}</ref> and embarked on the [[Happier Than Ever, The World Tour]] in February 2022, concluding it in April 2023.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Spanos |first=Brittany |date=February 4, 2022 |title=Opening night of the first Billie Eilish tour in two years was everything fans hoped for (plus rain) |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/billie-eilish-concert-review-happier-than-ever-tour-1294492/ |url-status=live |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220204141718/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/billie-eilish-concert-review-happier-than-ever-tour-1294492/ |archive-date=February 4, 2022 |access-date=August 1, 2022 |url-access=limited}}</ref>

In June 2021, Eilish was criticized online for videos in which she mouthed the anti-Asian slur "[[chink]]" while lip-syncing the song "[[Goblin (album)|Fish]]" by [[Tyler, the Creator]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Squires|first=Bethy|date=June 21, 2021|title=Billie Eilish Apologizes for Lip-Syncing Racist Slur in Old Video|url=https://www.vulture.com/2021/06/billie-eilish-apologizes-on-instagram-for-racist-language.html|access-date=July 21, 2021|website=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]|archive-date=July 21, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210721140455/https://www.vulture.com/2021/06/billie-eilish-apologizes-on-instagram-for-racist-language.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Yang|first=Rachel|date=June 22, 2021|title=Billie Eilish apologizes for mouthing anti-Asian slur in past video: 'I want to barf'|url=https://ew.com/music/billie-eilish-apologizes-anti-asian-slur/|access-date=July 21, 2021|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|archive-date=July 21, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210721140456/https://ew.com/music/billie-eilish-apologizes-anti-asian-slur/|url-status=live}}</ref> while Matthew Tyler Vorce, her reported boyfriend at the time, received criticism for alleged social media posts in which he used offensive language and slurs against gay and Black people.{{refn|<ref>{{cite news|last=Harrison|first=Ellie|date=June 18, 2021|title=Billie Eilish's reported boyfriend apologises after 'racist and homophobic' posts are resurfaced|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/billie-eilish-boyfriend-matthew-tyler-vorce-b1868340.html|access-date=July 21, 2021|website=[[The Independent]]|archive-date=July 21, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210721140456/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/billie-eilish-boyfriend-matthew-tyler-vorce-b1868340.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mier|first=Tomás|date=June 17, 2021|title=Billie Eilish's Boyfriend Matthew Tyler Vorce Apologizes After Racist and Homophobic Posts Resurface|url=https://people.com/music/billie-eilish-boyfriend-matthew-tyler-vorce-apologizes-offensive-comments/|access-date=July 21, 2021|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|archive-date=June 28, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210628022613/https://people.com/music/billie-eilish-boyfriend-matthew-tyler-vorce-apologizes-offensive-comments/|url-status=live}}</ref>}} Eilish was also accused of [[queerbaiting]] after using the caption "I love girls" to promote the music video for "Lost Cause".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/billie-eilish-fans-queerbaiting-claims-b1865639.html|title=Billie Eilish fans defend her against accusations of 'queerbaiting'|work=[[The Independent]]|first=Kate|last=Ng|date=June 14, 2021|access-date=April 9, 2024|url-status=live|archive-date=August 25, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210825072140/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/billie-eilish-fans-queerbaiting-claims-b1865639.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Robledo|first=Jordan|date=June 12, 2021|title=Billie Eilish uploads "I love girls" Instagram post after queer-baiting accusations|url=https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/billie-eilish-uploads-i-love-girls-instagram-post-after-queer-baiting-accusations/|access-date=July 21, 2021|website=[[Gay Times]]|archive-date=July 21, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210721140457/https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/billie-eilish-uploads-i-love-girls-instagram-post-after-queer-baiting-accusations/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Williams|first=Mae|date=June 14, 2021|title=Billie Eilish has been accused of queerbaiting in her 'Lost Cause' video|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/53183/1/billie-eilish-has-been-accused-of-queerbaiting-in-her-lost-cause-video|access-date=July 21, 2021|website=[[Dazed]]|archive-date=July 21, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210721140457/https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/53183/1/billie-eilish-has-been-accused-of-queerbaiting-in-her-lost-cause-video|url-status=live}}</ref> On June 22, she posted an apology to Instagram stories for her usage of "chink", saying that she was "appalled and embarrassed" by the video and that she was "13 or 14" at the time and did not know the slur was a derogatory term.<ref name="Kambhampaty-2021">{{cite news |last=Kambhampaty |first=Anna P. |date=June 22, 2021 |title=Billie Eilish Apologizes for Lip-Syncing Anti-Asian Slur |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/22/style/billie-eilish-asian-slur-apology.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/22/style/billie-eilish-asian-slur-apology.html |archive-date=December 28, 2021 |url-access=limited |access-date=July 21, 2021 |issn=0362-4331 |url-status=live}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref name="Burgess-2021">{{cite news|last=Burgess|first=Kaya|date=June 22, 2021|title=Billie Eilish apologises for racial slur in teenage video|newspaper=[[The Times]]|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/billie-eilish-apologises-for-racial-slur-in-teenage-video-rs6vstcks|access-date=December 16, 2021 |issn=0140-0460|archive-date=December 16, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211216011711/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/billie-eilish-apologises-for-racial-slur-in-teenage-video-rs6vstcks|url-status=live}}</ref> She also addressed a separate video of what was viewed as her mocking an Asian accent, writing that she was actually "speaking in a silly gibberish made up voice".<ref name="Kambhampaty-2021" /><ref name="Burgess-2021" /> Reflecting on the events in a July 2021 interview, Eilish said: "I said so many things then that I totally don't agree with now, or think the opposite thing. The weirdest thing is how nothing ever goes away once it's on the internet ... When you're a fucking teenager, you don't really know yourself ... I didn't actually know how I really felt. So I just came up with this facade that I stuck to."<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Lancaster|first=Brodie|date=July 17, 2021|title=Billie Eilish on her complicated relationship with the internet, the price of fame and the "new Billie"|url=https://www.vogue.com.au/culture/features/billie-eilish-on-her-complicated-relationship-with-the-internet-the-price-of-fame-and-the-new-billie/news-story/1c6e34914c93e17dd7299a8bd9aa1b5c|access-date=July 21, 2021|magazine=[[Vogue Australia]]|archive-date=July 20, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210720173512/https://www.vogue.com.au/culture/features/billie-eilish-on-her-complicated-relationship-with-the-internet-the-price-of-fame-and-the-new-billie/news-story/1c6e34914c93e17dd7299a8bd9aa1b5c|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:BillieEilishO2160622 (35 of 45) (52151963582) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Eilish during the [[Happier Than Ever, The World Tour]] (2022)]]

Eilish started formulating ideas for her third studio album's songs with Finneas in December 2021.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Robinson |first=Ellie |date=December 10, 2021 |title=Billie Eilish Has Already Started Writing Her Third Album with Brother Finneas |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/billie-eilish-has-already-started-writing-her-third-album-with-brother-finneas-3115562 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221018123723/https://www.nme.com/en_asia/news/music/billie-eilish-has-already-started-writing-her-third-album-with-brother-finneas-3115562 |archive-date=October 18, 2022 |access-date=October 18, 2022 |magazine=[[NME]]}}</ref> In a July 2022 interview with [[Zane Lowe]] for [[Apple Music]], she said she hoped to start writing the album in 2023.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=DeSantis |first=Rachel |date=July 21, 2022 |title=Billie Eilish Shares Two-Track Release ''Guitar Songs'': 'A Little Surprise' |url=https://people.com/music/billie-eilish-shares-two-track-release-guitar-songs/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220721213348/https://people.com/music/billie-eilish-shares-two-track-release-guitar-songs/ |archive-date=July 21, 2022 |access-date=August 13, 2022 |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]}}</ref> In 2022, Eilish won the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] for the song "[[No Time to Die (song)|No Time to Die]]" from the film [[No Time to Die|of the same name]], becoming the first person born in the 21st century to win an Academy Award.<ref name="Oscar"/> That same year, she became the youngest headliner to date for two festivals, specifically [[Glastonbury Festival 2022|Glastonbury]] and [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Savage |first=Mark |date=June 24, 2022 |title=Glastonbury 2022: Billie Eilish to make history as youngest-ever headliner |agency=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-61910835 |accessdate=June 24, 2022 |archive-date=June 24, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220624001101/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-61910835 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=January 13, 2022 |title=Coachella 2022: Kanye West, Billie Eilish and Harry Styles to Headline |agency=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-59982400 |access-date=October 26, 2022 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230517234839/https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-59982400 |archive-date=May 17, 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Pixar]] film ''[[Turning Red]]'' was released that year, for which she and Finneas wrote three songs, "[[Nobody Like U]]", "U Know What's Up" and "1 True Love", performed by ''Turning Red''{{'s}} fictional boy band 4*Town.<ref>{{cite web |last=Acuna |first=Kirsten |date=February 8, 2022 |title=Pixar sent Billie Eilish and Finneas O'Connell a boy band-inspired scrapbook to convince them to write music for their next animated movie, 'Turning Red' |url=https://www.insider.com/pixar-sent-billie-eilish-finneas-scrapbook-turning-red-pixar-2022-2 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20220317193441/https://www.insider.com/pixar-sent-billie-eilish-finneas-scrapbook-turning-red-pixar-2022-2 |archive-date=March 17, 2022 |work=[[Insider (website)|Insider]] |accessdate=March 15, 2022}}</ref>

In June 2022, during her world tour's Manchester show, Eilish debuted the then-unreleased ballad "TV". The song references [[Dobbs v. Jackson Women's Health Organization|the overturning]] of ''[[Roe v. Wade]]'', a case that made [[Abortion in the United States|abortion]] a [[constitutional right]] in the US.<ref name="Billboard-2022">{{cite magazine |date=June 9, 2022 |title=Billie Eilish Debuts New Ballad 'TV' During Manchester Show |url=https://www.billboard.com/video/billie-eilish-debuts-new-ballad-tv-during-manchester-show-billboard-news/ |url-status=live |magazine=Billboard |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220609184824/https://www.billboard.com/video/billie-eilish-debuts-new-ballad-tv-during-manchester-show-billboard-news/ |archive-date=June 9, 2022 |access-date=June 9, 2022}}</ref> The next month, on July 21, she [[Surprise release|surprise-released]] the two-track EP ''[[Guitar Songs]]'', which includes "TV" alongside "The 30th".<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Willman |first=Chris |date=July 21, 2022 |title=Billie Eilish Releases Two New Acoustic Tracks, 'TV' and 'The 30th,' Under ''Guitar Songs'' Umbrella |url=https://variety.com/2022/music/news/billie-eilish-releases-two-new-songs-tv-30th-guitar-songs-1235322117/ |access-date=August 1, 2022 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-date=July 21, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220721191827/https://variety.com/2022/music/news/billie-eilish-releases-two-new-songs-tv-30th-guitar-songs-1235322117/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Eilish explained her decision to surprise-release the EP during the interview with Lowe. She told him that while work on her third studio album was coming soon, she refused to wait until that time to put "TV" and "The 30th" on a track list. She wanted to spread their messages to her fans as soon as possible, noting the immediacy of its lyrics: "These songs are really current for me, and they're songs that I want to have said right now."<ref name="Rettig-2022">{{Cite web |last=Rettig |first=James |date=July 21, 2022 |title=Billie Eilish – 'TV' & 'The 30th' |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2193847/billie-eilish-tv-the-30th/music/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220721213351/https://www.stereogum.com/2193847/billie-eilish-tv-the-30th/music/ |archive-date=July 21, 2022 |access-date=July 21, 2022 |website=[[Stereogum]]}}</ref> Another reason was Eilish had grown tired of doing heavy, traditional promotion for upcoming music. She wanted to release songs like she had early in her career, previewing them for fans in live concerts before releasing them without much marketing.<ref name="TiredofPromo">{{Cite magazine |last=Rowley |first=Glenn |date=July 25, 2022 |title=Billie Eilish Confesses the Recording Studio Gives Her Anxiety: 'I Don't Enjoy It' |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/billie-eilish-anxiety-recording-studio-1235117638/ |url-status=live |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220801033726/https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/billie-eilish-anxiety-recording-studio-1235117638/ |archive-date=August 1, 2022 |access-date=August 6, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Rossignol |first=Derrick |date=July 21, 2022 |title=Billie Eilish Explains Abandoning Traditional 'Build-Up' to Surprise-Release 'TV' and 'The 30th' |url=https://uproxx.com/pop/billie-eilish-surprise-release-tv-30th/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220921201046/https://uproxx.com/pop/billie-eilish-surprise-release-tv-30th/ |archive-date=September 21, 2022 |access-date=October 19, 2022 |website=[[Uproxx]]}}</ref>

Eilish worked with [[Apple Music]] to exclusively host a film of one of the ''Happier Than Ever'' tour concerts, specifically one of her shows at [[The O2 Arena]] in London. She billed the film as a way for fans who missed out on tickets to experience the tour, wanting more people to recognize her showmanship live.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Aniftos |first=Rania |date=September 29, 2022 |title=Billie Eilish Shares Why Her Upcoming Concert Livestream Is 'Important' to Her: 'Touring Is an Extension of Me as an Artist' |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/billie-eilish-zane-lowe-interview-happier-than-ever-concert-livestream-1235146616/ |access-date=October 26, 2022 |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230517235738/https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/billie-eilish-zane-lowe-interview-happier-than-ever-concert-livestream-1235146616/ |archive-date=May 17, 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Lonsdale |first=John |date=September 30, 2022 |title=How to Watch Billie Eilish's 'Happier Than Ever' World Tour Livestream Concert on Apple Music |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/billie-eilish-happier-than-ever-livestream-concert-watch-free-1234602977/ |access-date=October 26, 2022 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230517235649/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/billie-eilish-happier-than-ever-livestream-concert-watch-free-1234602977/ |archive-date=May 17, 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Young |first=David James |date=September 27, 2022 |title=Billie Eilish to Commemorate End of ''Happier Than Ever'' World Tour with Apple Music Livestream |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/billie-eilish-to-commemorate-end-of-happier-than-ever-world-tour-with-apple-music-livestream-3317487 |access-date=October 26, 2022 |magazine=[[NME]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221026030503/https://www.nme.com/news/music/billie-eilish-to-commemorate-end-of-happier-than-ever-world-tour-with-apple-music-livestream-3317487 |archive-date=October 26, 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref> Three concerts, titled Happier Than Ever, The Hometown Encore, were held at the [[Kia Forum]] in [[Inglewood, California]], from December 13 to 16, 2022, as part of the tour.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Fu |first=Eddie |date=October 18, 2022 |title=Billie Eilish Announces Final 2022 Tour Dates |url=https://consequence.net/2022/10/billie-eilish-final-2022-tour-dates/ |access-date=October 26, 2022 |website=[[Consequence (publication)|Consequence]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230518094631/https://consequence.net/2022/10/billie-eilish-final-2022-tour-dates/ |archive-date=May 18, 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Helfand |first=Raphael |date=October 18, 2022 |title=Billie Eilish Announces Two Hometown Shows |url=https://www.thefader.com/2022/10/18/billie-eilish-happier-than-ever-hometown-encore |access-date=October 26, 2022 |magazine=[[The Fader]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230518095129/https://www.thefader.com/2022/10/18/billie-eilish-happier-than-ever-hometown-encore |archive-date=May 18, 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2023, Eilish made her acting debut in the [[Amazon Prime Video]] satirical thriller series ''[[Swarm (TV series)|Swarm]]''.<ref name="Lambe-2023" /> She starred as Eva, the leader of a cult inspired by [[NXIVM]], and received positive reviews for her performance.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Frank |first=Allegra |date=March 17, 2023 |title=Billie Eilish Kicks Off Acting Career With Incredible 'Swarm' Episode |work=The Daily Beast |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/obsessed/billie-eilish-in-swarm-guide-to-her-cult-leader-character |access-date=March 19, 2023 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230518095541/https://www.thedailybeast.com/obsessed/billie-eilish-in-swarm-guide-to-her-cult-leader-character |archive-date=May 18, 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref>

Eilish wrote the song "[[What Was I Made For?]]" for the soundtrack of the 2023 film ''[[Barbie (film)|Barbie]]''. According to statements posted on her social media, she was inspired to write the song after seeing unfinished scenes of the movie during its production.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Aniftos |first=Rania |date=September 29, 2022 |title=Billie Eilish Shares Self-Directed Video for 'Barbie' Ballad 'What Was I Made For?' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/billie-eilish-video-barbie-song-what-was-i-made-for-1234787731/ |access-date=October 26, 2022 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]] |archive-date=October 3, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231003225410/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/billie-eilish-video-barbie-song-what-was-i-made-for-1234787731/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2024, the song won the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] and two [[Grammy Awards]] for [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media|Best Song Written for Visual Media]]. It became the tenth song in history to win both an Academy Award for Best Original Song and a Grammy Award for Song of the Year, and Eilish became the youngest person ever to win two [[Academy Awards]] in any category.<ref name="WhatWasIMadeFor" />

=== 2024–present: ''Hit Me Hard and Soft'' ===
{{Main|Hit Me Hard and Soft}}
On April 8, 2024, Eilish announced her third studio album, ''[[Hit Me Hard and Soft]]'', which was released on May 17, 2024.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Dailey |first=Hannah |date=2024-04-08 |title=Billie Eilish Announces Third Album 'Hit Me Hard and Soft': Here's When It Arrives |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/billie-eilish-new-album-hit-me-hard-and-soft-release-date-1235651340/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240408170029/https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/billie-eilish-new-album-hit-me-hard-and-soft-release-date-1235651340/ |archive-date=2024-04-08 |access-date=2024-04-08 |magazine=Billboard |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Martoccio |first=Angie |date=2024-04-08 |title=The Wait Is Over: Billie Eilish Announces New Album 'Hit Me Hard and Soft' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/billie-eilish-new-album-hit-me-hard-and-soft-1234998028/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240408160413/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/billie-eilish-new-album-hit-me-hard-and-soft-1234998028/ |archive-date=2024-04-08 |access-date=2024-04-08 |magazine=Rolling Stone |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Spotify |url=https://open.spotify.com/album/7aJuG4TFXa2hmE4z1yxc3n?si=tUHQq4J6S3Oxr-dZqFiZ4A |access-date=2024-05-17 |website=open.spotify.com |archive-date=May 17, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240517090055/https://open.spotify.com/album/7aJuG4TFXa2hmE4z1yxc3n?si=tUHQq4J6S3Oxr-dZqFiZ4A |url-status=live }}</ref> She announced a tour to support the album, [[Hit Me Hard and Soft: The Tour]], on April 29, 2024, with concerts in North America, Oceania and Europe between September 2024 and July 2025.<ref name="HMHASannouncement"/> Also in April, Eilish was announced to be the next 'featured artist' inside of ''[[Fortnite]]'' spin-off game, ''[[Fortnite Festival]]'', along with an unlockable outfit in the game.<ref>{{cite web |title=Billie Eilish will be the bad guy in Fortnite |url=https://www.theverge.com/2024/4/22/24137317/billie-eilish-fortnite-festival-date |first=Andrew |last=Webster |date=22 April 2024 |access-date=23 April 2024 |website=[[The Verge]] |archive-date=April 23, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240423010739/https://www.theverge.com/2024/4/22/24137317/billie-eilish-fortnite-festival-date |url-status=live }}</ref>

